  pmid={40519092},
  keywords={NAD, depletion, interferon, cGAS-STING, mitochondrial DNA, VDAC1, innate immunity},
  note={In vitro; NIH3T3, IMR90 human, HS5 stromal cells. Chronic NAD depletion (nicotinamide removal) causes: NAD+ falls to less than 10 percent of control within days; mitochondrial DNA leaks into cytoplasm via VDAC1; cGAS-STING activation; Type I interferon gene expression. Cells remain viable but have reduced spare respiratory capacity and impaired glycolysis. Mechanistically bridges NAD+ depletion to viral-infection-like immune activation. Relevant to ME/CFS: if chronic partial NAD+ depletion occurs, this pathway could explain persistent interferon-like immune signature even after virus clearance.},
